[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(22) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "No bondmen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—This exemption, however it may have continued in theory, must virtually have been set aside in the later days of Solomon. (See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 12:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) They are here described as occupying the position of a dominant race—as warriors, servants about the person of the king, princes, and officers in the array—like the free vassals under a feudal monarchy. But as the absolute power of the king increased, and with it, perhaps, the wealth and arrogance of his favourites and greater officers, the condition of the Israelites at large might be removed from serfship more in name than in reality. Even the subject races might be played of against them, as against the Macedonians in the later years of Alexander the Great, when his royalty passed into something like a true Oriental despotism. Certainly, in later times we find, both from the history and the prophetical books, that there was such a thing as serf ship of the poor to the princes. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 34:8-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 5:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:22-23",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 9:22-23",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Of the children of Israel did Solomon make no bond-men",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — He spared them, and did not employ them in any servile labours about his public works, but put them into nobler offices, as it here follows. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They were men of war — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Which was accounted an honourable employment. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And his servants — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Officers in his court. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And his princes — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Governors of provinces. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And his captains, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — Commanders of his guards. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Five hundred and fifty ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 8:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", they are said to be but two hundred and fifty. But perhaps the meaning there is, that there were two hundred and fifty set over those that wrought in the temple; the rest probably being employed in overseeing his public works in other places. And it must be observed also, that there were far greater numbers employed when the temple work was carried on with great speed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
